The paper discusses the use of deep convolutional neural networks (DCNNs) in object recognition tasks, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also focuses on the addition of a top-down attention layer to DCNNs, which involves modifying the network architecture and could be considered a form of neural network engineering (cs.NE). The evaluation of the attention layer's effects on sensitivity and bias in object recognition tasks involves statistical analysis and machine learning techniques (cs.LG). The paper's motivation from neuroscience research and discussion of attention mechanisms could also be relevant to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-categories.
